{"name":"4. SINISTER CREATURE OPTIONS","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Monsters Mythica: Black-Eyed Child","type":"text","_id":"sft14KecdhxyUmKR","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>@UUID[Actor.MmH2oVwHg9fP4kNp]{Black-eyed Child}</p><p></p><blockquote><p>“They came from the road already pleading to be let in. Before I could ask why two children were traveling alone at night, their begging turned to screams, then to howling and pounding on the gates. I felt the ramparts shaking under my feet as I turned to sound the alarm. When I looked back, they were gone as suddenly as they’d appeared.”</p><p>~ From the report of Falen Cooper, wall guard</p></blockquote><p></p><p>Black-eyed children are widely regarded as a myth. A tale told by road-weary travelers to entertain tavern goers and encourage the flow of free ale. But these child-like fiends are all too real and spend their lives roaming roads and paths in search of well-meaning people to fall prey to their insidious guise.</p><p></p><blockquote><p>Our <a href=\"https://undergroundoracle.com/tag/monsters-mythica/\">Monsters Mythica</a> series provides reimagined monsters from myth and urban legends as 5e-compatible creatures ready for your fantasy setting.</p></blockquote><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/black_eye_child.png\" width=\"116\" height=\"256\" /><p></p><h2><strong>Kind Spirits, Delicious Hearts</strong></h2><p>Black-Eyed Children are the embodiment of treachery and vile trickery, assuming the form of innocent children in need of rescue in order to consume the spiritual energies and, eventually, the flesh of those good enough to offer them help. Once the children have successfully ensnared their victim, they will slowly drain them of their essence until they’re too weak to fight off their needle-like teeth and claws.</p><p>There have been stories of entire caravans slowly succumbing to and being ravaged by groups of black-eyed children, and these bloody tales have been so effective in certain parts of the continent that it’s seen as bad luck to help lone children on the road. While those stories have been sufficient in deterring those with more hardened hearts, it’s done nothing to stop the soft hearts the children are hunting for.</p><h2><strong>Problem Children</strong></h2><p>Although they can be found alone, black-eyed children are normally summoned in pairs and prefer to travel in small groups of four or five. Given their incredibly chaotic and bloodthirsty natures, black-eyed children are one of the least reliable demons to summon, using any tricks or avenues available to them to break free from their masters and run rampant on the Prime Material. While on the Lower Planes, black-eyed children spend their time plotting and searching for ways to get to the Prime Material. Since they’re rarely summoned outright, they generally accomplish this through assisting greater demons and devils in their schemes, finding gates or portals, and taking advantage of the mistakes of naive or inexperienced cultists.</p><p></p><p>@UUID[Actor.MmH2oVwHg9fP4kNp]{Black-eyed Child}</p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/byc_statblock.png\" />","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Monsters Mythica: Dread Coachman","type":"text","_id":"9Dy5Nzc0o2NFnxPa","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>@UUID[Actor.V1uPutZd3SDbs09D]{Dread Coachman}</p><p></p><blockquote><p>“Have I been cursed? Once again I was upon the ramparts on Pallowen, and once again, the gods granted me a terrible vision. I was doing my patrols when the air grew so chill I thought I would freeze in my armor. Suddenly I heard a terrible racket from above and looked up to see a carriage, pulled by spectral horses and driven by a coachman so horrible I thought my heart would seize up. I watched as he passed over one of my fellow guards and pulled him into his wretched cart before vanishing into the night sky. I will never forget it. And I will certainly be switching shifts next year.”</p><p>- From the report of Falen Cooper, wall guard</p></blockquote><p></p><p>The crack of a whip. The terrible clattering of hooves cutting through the still night air. The ghastly inevitability of what this creature of retribution carries with it in its loathsome carriage. These are the details of stories whispered by cutthroats in back alleys and by bandits around their campfires. Tales of punishment for crimes left unanswered and of victims left unavenged. Beware, they say, with their eyes turned toward the starless sky and what it holds beyond its borders. Beware the dread coachman.</p><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/dread_coachman2.png\" /><p></p><h2><strong>Soul Collector</strong></h2><p>A dread coachman, or collector of souls as it’s called in some regions around the continent, is not only a harbinger of death but of eternal punishment. Sent from beyond the realms of mortal men to bring retribution from vengeful gods or otherworldly beings, once a dread coachman has been tasked with a bounty, they cannot return to their masters empty-handed. There is no stretch of the Prime Material that their victims could go where the dread coachman would not find them. Once they have discovered their target, they make their intentions known by calling out their name and their crimes in a voice that resonates within the chests of all who can hear it. After that, it’s only a matter of time before they're within the dark oblivion of the dread coachman’s carriage, never to be seen again.</p><p>Not even death can dissuade the dread coachman, as it’s sometimes sent to gather lost souls wandering through the planes to bring them in for their final judgments, especially those that led dark lives and have failed to move on to their gods.</p><p>Through the popularity of the folklore surrounding it, this particular wraith has gained a reputation for bringing evil men to meet their ultimate justice, but the truth is a far grimmer matter. The dread coachman is an amoral creature, only capable of carrying out the acts of revenge directed to it by its master, whether those commands are truly just or not. Villain or hero, guilty or innocent, once their taskmaster has delivered their judgment, the dread coachman can only obey.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Broken Bonds</strong></h2><p>The dread coachman’s imprisonment to the whims of their master begins at their creation, which occurs when the follower or servant of a god or other immortal betrays their sacred covenant. Regardless of whether the betrayal was purposeful or inadvertent, the punishment is the same; an infinity of horrid servitude.</p><p>There are rare circumstances when the bonds between a dread coachman and their commander are severed, usually through planar events or powerful artifactual magic. When this happens, the creature begins to rot and is driven entirely into darkness, harvesting as many souls as it can and growing in power and maliciousness until it is finally driven from the plane. Or, in the worst instances, until it is bound to a more nefarious source on the Prime Material.</p><p></p><section id=\"secret-ac3hMr3R0dhGAylm\" class=\"secret\"><p><strong>GM NOTES: WHIP OF SORROWS</strong></p><p>When a dread coachman is defeated, they’re driven back to their plane of origin, leaving behind their primary weapon, the whip of all sorrows.</p><p>@UUID[Item.u5r4IJerJxl91gsz]{Whip of All Sorrows}</p><p><strong>Whip of All Sorrows</strong></p><p>Weapon (Whip), Rare (Requires Attunement)</p><p>This ghoulish whip is made from the polished bones of a multitude of different humanoids and ends in a cruel barb.</p><p>While attuned to this whip, you have resistance to necrotic damage, and this weapon does an additional 2d8 necrotic damage.</p></section><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/dread_coachman.png\" /><p></p><h2><strong>Plot Hooks</strong></h2><p>The following are plot hooks you can use to introduce or interact with this new creature:</p><p>• “Call the guards! The bloody coachman is here for me, and I’ve done nothing wrong!” As the dread coachman passes through the house the woman ran out of, cold air hits you, and the smell of putrid death comes along with it.</p><p>• You’re stopped by the local sheriff as you pass her building. She tells you that she’s noticed how you hold yourself and how well-armed you are and says she’s looking for assistance. “A flying carriage has been seen over the past few weeks, and each time it’s reported, people come up missing. Could you help us find out what’s happening?”.</p><p>• As you’re walking down the road, you suddenly hear your name being called out. It echoes in the air and reverberates through your chest. “Your name has been given, and I have come to collect your soul!”</p><p>• After traveling through the mountains for some time, you come upon a strange carriage with a missing wheel. From behind it, a voice calls out, “Do not fear me, for I have not come for you. The one I seek has done much evil against both humanity and the gods.” A hideous coachman steps from behind the carriage and continues speaking. “But I could use your assistance.”</p><p>• As you stop in the city, you see a post that reads, “Only the brave should apply. Saviors needed to face and defeat a ghastly magical creature. It and its carriage have somehow been trapped inside old farmer MiCallan’s barn outside of town. All previous attempts to destroy it have failed. Upon completion of this mission, the heroes would receive our eternal gratitude and much gratuity. Report to Governor Ernistall at the courthouse with interest.”</p><p></p><p>@UUID[Actor.V1uPutZd3SDbs09D]{Dread Coachman}</p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/dread_coachman_statblock.png\" /><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Monsters Mythica: Terrors of the Deep Woods - Bunny Man","type":"text","_id":"JL15BnLKLqipsetq","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p>There are woods so deep and so dark they mirror the ocean in their mystery and grandeur. Where creatures who count their years in the crumbling of stone rather than in the passing of seasons dwell without their strange ways and alien natures ever being witnessed by the prying eyes of humanity. Even the thought of traveling through the midnight darkness of these great forests causes the boldest of adventurers to stifle a bone-deep shiver they cannot attribute to any breeze.</p><p>Whispers abound around campfires and in drink halls of the terrors caused when one of these dread denizens takes it upon itself to travel outside of its woodland domain but to willingly step through the places they call home is unthinkable. Out among the looming red oaks and tar-stained pines, there are terrors waiting where men were not meant to tread.</p><p>The following are creatures that can be encountered while traveling through any dark and foreboding forest.</p><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/bunnyman.png\" width=\"313\" height=\"389\" /><h1><strong>Bunny Man</strong></h1><p>@UUID[Actor.t07GGgf6ZSliFY76]{Bunny Man}</p><p></p><blockquote><p>“Ragged are their clothes, and ragged are their souls, for they know no rest. They are revenants seeking themselves. Tasked to roam the unhallowed woods, forever seeking their own kin.”</p><p>~ Egress Varn, High Priest of the Eternal Ember Temple</p></blockquote><p></p><p>Tales of what punishments befall mortals who break the sanctity of enchanted lands are plentiful. Hunters who mark a sacred beast as their prey. Woodsmen who fell the wrong tree in a grove. Guardians of the earthen realms who fail their lords in their solemn duties. All must pay a price in order to prevent future transgressions from their kind. But none have paid so heavily as the ones they call the bunny men.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Cursed Guardians</strong></h2><p>Bunny men are hulking, malevolent creatures, cursed by fey or similar otherworldly beings for perceived trespasses against the flora and fauna within their domains. A cruel amalgam of hare and humanoid, bunny men are stripped of any mercy, benevolence, or reason that they once possessed and doomed to act as guardians in the lands that they offended, hunting down and eliminating anyone foolish or careless enough to wander into the territories they’ve been loosed upon.</p><p>Typically cursed and created by evil fey, bunny men are highly valued by deep woods hags and their adjacent ilk for both their bloodthirsty natures and ceaseless capabilities. Along with any thread of goodness that once remained in the wretched creatures, bunny men are deprived of their ability to sleep or rest, instead tasked with endlessly searching and surveying the lands of their masters for any potential threats or victims they might find there. A fell combination of finely-honed skill and bequeathed magics, bunny men are master hunters. Perfectly suited to force their way through any obstacle or hindrance set before them, once a bunny man has sighted their prey, they cannot stop their pursuit until either they or their target has been returned to the dark soil.</p><p>The bunny men’s tool of choice for their grim business is the same no matter what their long-forgotten origins may have been — a woodsmen’s axe, larger and sharper than any that they would have wielded in their past life and dripping with steady rivulets of blood that seep from the head of the weapon itself. It’s said that with every drop of blood that falls from their axe, another piece of who they once were is lost to the ether. Whether or not that is true, in the rare moments that a bunny man gains some small semblance of lucidity, it comes as more curse than blessing.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Bloodsoaked Relief</strong></h2><p>When a bunny man has achieved their singular goal, their axe slick with blood brought from outside of the woods they are forsaken to protect, they’re allowed a brief moment of bittersweet rest. Standing among the remains of the lives they snuffed out, their muscles go slack, their mind slows, and they lose themselves to whatever place these tortured and tortuous creatures go in these scarce moments. In this trance-like state, the bunny man remembers. Remembers who they once were, what events led them to their cursed shape and the many wicked things they have been charged to do since then. And, in the face of the infinite sadness of that tiny moment, they remember how to scream. It’s during this time that truly vicious and vengeful creators might visit their inconsolable warden, making promises of an eventual release from their curse and reinstatement of the life they lost before committing their terrible crimes against the earthen realm. These are, of course, lies and further cruelties that the bunny man will forget by sunrise. On the rare occasion that a bunny man has outlived their usefulness to their master, they are turned wholly into a hare. Fulfilling the fey’s darkest sense of humor and finally making the full transformation from predator to prey.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Harvestable Materials:</strong></h2><p></p><h3><strong>Bunny Man’s Axe</strong></h3><p>@UUID[Item.qYTqJsseiV0YyH35]{Bunny Man's Axe}</p><p><em><strong>Weapon (Greataxe), Rare (Requires Attunement)</strong></em></p><p>You gain a +2 bonus to attack and damage rolls made with this magic weapon.</p><p>When you roll a maximum result on the damage die for an attack you make with this axe, the target creature must make a Constitution saving throw whose DC is equal to 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Strength modifier. On a failure, the creature is knocked back 5 feet and begins to bleed, taking additional slashing damage equal to your Strength modifier at the start of each of their subsequent turns until they succeed on their Constitution saving throw.</p><p><em><strong>Cursed.</strong></em> The moment you attune to the axe, you can feel the curse that once afflicted the bunny man course through you as you begin your slow transformation. If your attunement to this weapon is not removed by the next new moon, you will transform fully into a bunny man at full health and under the GM's control. Once you have made this transformation, only a wish spell or divine intervention can restore you to your former state.</p><p></p><p>@UUID[Actor.t07GGgf6ZSliFY76]{Bunny Man}</p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/bunnyman_axe.png\" />","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":400000,"name":"Monsters Mythica: Terrors of the Deep Woods - Not Deer","type":"text","_id":"dhfO5t5S2Rt9CHn1","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">There are woods so deep and so dark they mirror the ocean in their mystery and grandeur. Where creatures who count their years in the crumbling of stone rather than in the passing of seasons dwell without their strange ways and alien natures ever being witnessed by the prying eyes of humanity. Even the thought of traveling through the midnight darkness of these great forests causes the boldest of adventurers to stifle a bone-deep shiver they cannot attribute to any breeze.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Whispers abound around campfires and in drink halls of the terrors caused when one of these dread denizens takes it upon itself to travel outside of its woodland domain but to willingly step through the places they call home is unthinkable. Out among the looming red oaks and tar-stained pines, there are terrors waiting where men were not meant to tread.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The following are creatures that can be encountered while traveling through any dark and foreboding forest.</span></p><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/notdeer.png\" width=\"456\" height=\"537\" /><h1><br class=\"Apple-interchange-newline\" /><strong>Not Deer</strong></h1><p>@UUID[Actor.gR1A5PyqXqAJwcoZ]{Not Deer}</p><p></p><blockquote><p>“I’ve walked these woods more often than I can count. I know its hills and valleys and the things that live there better than I know my mother’s face. What that creature may have been, I cannot say. But I can tell you one thing for certain, my friend. It wasn’t any deer.”</p><p>- Allendon Mayersiel, ranger of Gillshire</p></blockquote><p></p><p>All creatures dream. From the snakes slithering their way through the underbrush, to the owls roosted high in the hollows of maple trees, to the squirrels that get caught by either somewhere in between. The particulars that make up the wild dreamscapes that these beasts roam are unknown to most, but it’s their nightmares that mortals must be wary of. When the creatures of the woods touch that dread plane in unison, in the face of a threat to them all, the nightmares they produce can be made flesh and bone. Nightmares that almost reflect their own kind. Nightmares like the not deer.</p><p></p><section id=\"secret-gOx6Qvetxt17cxkj\" class=\"secret\"><p><em><strong>GM NOTES: OPHCIPHAEL, THE PLANE OF NIGHTMARES</strong></em></p><p>In the cosmology of Quaseloth, the Underground Oracle campaign setting, Ophciphael is a shifting plane of nightmares created when a vengeful celestial being destroyed itself to punish the sins of mortals.</p></section><p></p><h2><strong>Unnatural Response</strong></h2><p>Not deer are denizens of Ophciphael, the Plane of Nightmares. Created by the coalesced fear and mental anguish of groups of creatures crying out together in their dreams, these monstrous beings are an unnatural response to equally unnatural threats faced by the forest. Arcane disasters blighting the land, clearcutting and razing to make way for the progress of humanity, stygian energies oozing from a tear in the planes that corrupts the natural order. Any of these events could give rise to a not deer.</p><p>Although given form on Ophciphael, not deer cannot physically manifest on the Prime Material without first being born. Entering the womb of a pregnant doe through the dreams of her unborn, the not deer waits, slowly draining the life from one of the unfortunate fawns within and eventually taking its place alongside its sibling. The resulting labor is a bloody and loathsome affair that encapsulates the trauma and turmoil that gave the creature its very essence. After its true birth, the not deer rises from the gore-slicked ground on too-steady legs with too many joints and takes its place among its new family.</p><p>Despite their wholly unnatural and unsettling presence, the creatures the not deer surrounds themselves with do not appear to notice or care about their newest herd member’s physical or behavioral irregularities. Like all nightmares, the not deer is an inherently insidious creature, able to twist and manipulate the perceptions of those around it so only the most enchanted beast or earthen creature would be able to discern its true nature. The not deer assumes an adult form overnight and, after driving any competing bucks or predators in the area to destroy themselves in fits of froth-spitting rage and frenzy, takes its place at the center of the herd. And it begins to feed.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Fear Eater</strong></h2><p>Not deer consume the psychic energy of living creatures around them, siphoning their discomfort, fear, and pain to sustain themselves. Although the beasts of the forest offer little in the way of intelligence, in large enough numbers, the not deer can still gorge itself without fully depleting its food source. Perfectly willing to disrupt the natural order, the not deer will lead its herd into disease, famine, and catastrophe so that it might enjoy a heartier meal while remaining careful not to let the bulk of its resources succumb to their circumstances. Not deer will even go so far as to assist in whatever disaster created it if it’s able, or at the very least, keep anyone from attempting to remedy the situation.</p><p>When faced with an intelligent threat, the not deer will employ the same mind-clouding methods and eldritch subterfuge it does on the beasts around it, but instead of savoring this new meal it will seek to fully consume and destroy the mind of its foe as soon as is possible. Unwilling to let its presence be known for risk of being ejected from the plane, the not deer will use every tool in its nightmarish arsenal to protect itself and destroy its enemies, including calling on its false family to defy their instincts and viciously attack its adversaries.</p><p></p><h2 data-anchor=\"harvestable-materials:\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:1rem 0px 0.5rem;padding:0px;font-weight:normal;font-size:1.5em;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header);color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Harvestable Materials:</strong></span></h2><p></p><h3><strong>Not Deer Antler</strong></h3><p>@UUID[Item.yJv3c49Te8sya8ef]{Not Deer Antler}</p><p>When it is destroyed, the not deer is shunted back to the Plane of Nightmares, leaving behind a rancid-smelling puddle of dark purple ooze and a single piece of antler.</p><p><em><strong>Wondrous Item, Very Rare (Requires Attunement)</strong></em></p><p>This antler can be used as a spellcasting focus. The saving throw DC of spells you cast when using the antler increases by 2.</p><p>When you cast a spell that deals psychic damage or causes the frightened condition, target creatures have disadvantage on any required saving throws for that spell.</p><p><em><strong>Cursed.</strong></em> When you attune to this antler, you are given vivid and painful visions of the terrors that stalk Ophciphael, the Plane of Nightmares. You are only able to complete a long rest once every 48 hours. This effect lasts until the curse is removed and you break attunement to the antler.</p><p></p><p>@UUID[Actor.gR1A5PyqXqAJwcoZ]{Not Deer}</p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/notdeer_statblock.png\" /><p></p><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":500000,"name":"Monsters Mythica: Terrors of the Deep Woods - White Thing","type":"text","_id":"zJJp37phl63UTxoP","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">There are woods so deep and so dark they mirror the ocean in their mystery and grandeur. Where creatures who count their years in the crumbling of stone rather than in the passing of seasons dwell without their strange ways and alien natures ever being witnessed by the prying eyes of humanity. Even the thought of traveling through the midnight darkness of these great forests causes the boldest of adventurers to stifle a bone-deep shiver they cannot attribute to any breeze.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Whispers abound around campfires and in drink halls of the terrors caused when one of these dread denizens takes it upon itself to travel outside of its woodland domain but to willingly step through the places they call home is unthinkable. Out among the looming red oaks and tar-stained pines, there are terrors waiting where men were not meant to tread.</span></p><p style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:0.5em 0px;min-height:1rem;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:12.25px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">The following are creatures that can be encountered while traveling through any dark and foreboding forest.</span></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/white_thing.png\" /><p></p><h1><strong>White Thing</strong></h1><p>@UUID[Actor.cIjAdP7it4ik4gXR]{White Things}</p><p></p><blockquote><p>“I thought that leaving my position on the wall and setting out well before Pallowen would save me. But where did I find myself on the evening? Guarding a caravan of wine and silks and praying to the gods I made it to morning. Those white devils trailed us for miles. Weaving in and out of the trees and vanishing from sight in a blink. Until the day I die, I’ll remember those howls. But not nearly as clearly as Jonathan’s screams as they drug him into the night.”</p><p>~ From the report of Falen Cooper, transport guard</p></blockquote><p></p><p>While traveling through the wilds or on vacant trails along towering woods, a noisy night can be a true blessing. The sounds of animals filling the air may be disconcerting to people better acquainted with life inside city walls than without, but for well-worn travelers, the sounds of nature are the sounds of normalcy. It’s the still nights that are truly terrifying. When the wind seems nervous to come as more than a whisper and the moonless sky hangs heavy and stifling overhead. It’s on those nights the true monsters are about, waiting to pierce that unnatural silence with their ragged, shrieking howls.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Monstrous Bloodline</strong></h2><p>White things resemble many-limbed wolves the size of bears. They roam far and wide through their wooded territories, perpetually trying to sate their nearly endless lust for rending and feasting on flesh and bone. Consummate killers, white things will gladly tear their way through herds of prey animals or even apex predators foolish enough to see the white things as nothing more than rival beasts. But although their environments are flush with creatures ripe for the picking, the white things are always drawn back to the source of their first taste of blood.</p><p>Before they were the terrible beings they are today, the first white things were a different sort of monster altogether. A small family of nobles known for their heavy-handed handling of the people under their banner and the battle￾hungry way they acquired new territory around their lands, they were as fierce as they were cold and cared only for those that shared their bloodline. They had been skirmishing for months with a small group of resistance fighters in the hills of their newest territory when the matriarch of the noble family had finally had enough. Leading the charge herself with her children beside her, they razed the hillside without any regard for the people there, eventually forcing the leaders of the resistance to turn themselves over in an attempt to stop the wanton violence.</p><p>As the leaders of the resistance stood bound on the gallows, the gloating matriarch allowed them to say their final words before sending them on to oblivion. The eldest of the resistance, a man whose back bent double under the weight of the years he carried, stepped forward and used his dying words to cry out a curse, begging his god to reveal these devil’s dogs as the monsters they truly were. And as the old man’s rope went taut, it punctuated his prayer with a sound like a thunderclap that was said to be heard for miles before settling into an unnatural silence. The air then filled with the shrieking howls of the matriarch and her noble family and the desperate cries of their men.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Silent Night</strong></h2><p>After tearing their soldiers to unrecognizable shreds, the white things abandoned their realm for woodlands that suited their new forms and hungers, spreading through the darkest woodlands over the centuries that followed and terrorizing travelers foolish enough to brave the night. When the moon is new, white things slip silently through the forest and along roadsides, fading in and out of the trees like a fog and trailing unsuspecting parties until the perfect time to strike. What they may lack in the intelligence their ancestors once possessed, the white things make up for with bestial instinct, flesh-rending claws, and the ability to seemingly fade into and out of thin air when they please.</p><p>It’s said that when the white things are on the prowl, the night goes dead silent, as though the entire world and all of the living things in it were holding their breath. Seasoned caravaners and travelers know to be wary when the night gets too quiet and to prepare for the white things to come. But the truly wise know that when their shrieking howls cut through the night air, it’s already too late.</p><p></p><h2 data-anchor=\"harvestable-materials:\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;margin:1rem 0px 0.5rem;padding:0px;font-weight:normal;font-size:1.5em;border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-underline-header);color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\"><strong style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\">Harvestable Materials:</strong></span></h2><p></p><h3><strong>Pelt of the White Thing</strong></h3><p>@UUID[Item.ZBBOQUMNPq6u5ZJC]{Pelt of the White Thing}</p><p>When a white thing is killed, it falls to the ground the same way as any natural animal, and although its pelt can be harvested from its carcass, there is nothing natural about it.</p><p><em><strong>Wondrous Item, Rare (Requires Attunement)</strong></em></p><p>Your Dexterity and Strength each increase by 2 (the pelt may increase these scores above 20), and you gain resistance to bludgeoning, piercing, and slashing damage from nonmagical attacks that aren't silvered.</p><p>While wearing this pelt, you can transform your hands into savage claws to make an unarmed strike as a bonus action. If you hit with your claws, you can deal slashing damage equal to 1d6 + your Strength modifier instead of the bludgeoning damage normal for an unarmed strike.</p><p><em><strong>Cursed.</strong></em> As you attune to this pelt, your mouth fills with the taste of blood as an ear-shattering howl cuts through your mind. You gain vulnerability to attacks from silvered weapons. Additionally, you enter a mindless and frenzied state during combat. You must use your action each turn to attempt to damage a hostile creature. When there are no more hostile creatures to attack during combat, for a number of rounds equal to your Strength modifier, you will use your action to attack any creatures near you. If you can make extra attacks as part of the Attack action, you must use those extra attacks, moving to attack the next nearest creature if your current target falls. This effect remains until the curse is removed and you break attunement to the pelt.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Plot Hooks</strong></h2><p>The following are plot hooks you can use to introduce these woodland horrors to your group of adventurers.</p><p>• A local man named Terrel Lawrence went on a hunting trip into the woods several weeks ago but has yet to return. His family is looking for a brave group of folks to mount a search party and bring him home.</p><p>• A commotion in the center of town has set off the alarm bells and sent the guards running toward the source of turmoil. As a woman runs by, she screams that there’s a rabbit monster hacking people apart!Animals in the area have been behaving strangely, attacking hunters and each other without regard to their natural instincts. The village elder needs someone to find out what’s causing this behavior before someone is seriously hurt.</p><p>• Progress has stopped on the construction of the king’s newest road, with the workers in the camp at the forest’s edge reporting terrible weakness and the inability to sleep due to terrifying nightmares.</p><p>• Local farmers report that some sort of fiend or ghost is tearing their livestock to shreds. Witnesses say that the monsters are white as snow and disappear as you look at them. A young member of the Colossi, a renowned monster hunters guild, is looking for assistance in tracking down a group of white things that are terrifying caravaners on the high road.</p><p></p><p>@UUID[Actor.cIjAdP7it4ik4gXR]{White Things}</p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/white_thing_statblock.png\" />","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.288","createdTime":1667083255669,"modifiedTime":1667786404489,"lastModifiedBy":"zr7Ai9kVc0jXui9g"},"_id":"3LU2sPcRUAi8hV6j","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"YQ88Zx2ssDk4TvZ2":3}}
{"name":"3. EERIE PLAYER OPTIONS","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Lineage: Terrorborn","type":"text","_id":"8H8XgotkgmY1OQgT","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<blockquote><p>They were a person once, weren’t they? They could remember men and women, faces young and old running the gamut of expressions in their mind. They could even remember some of their names. Too many names. Was one of them theirs? How very curious, they thought.</p><p>Why had they never noticed these colors? So bright and so many in their shades and tones. Had there always been so many? And the scents, and the sounds, and the feeling of their feet on the ground. The feeling of their skin on their muscle on their bone. These they remembered, didn’t they? They tried to catch one of the chaotic memories skittering through their mind, something recalling all of these myriad sensations. But they came away from the rolling swarm of thoughts with only essences. Like a close friend describing a feeling rather than the feeling itself.</p><p>Friends. Those they remembered. Little sparks of light in a darkness so thick and clinging and intense that breaking free of it was like being born.</p><p>They would find their friends.</p></blockquote><p></p><p>The Plane of Nightmares is a labyrinthian miasma composed of the multitudes of fears and terrors of the creatures of the planes. From the panic of prey animals fleeing snapping jaws to the creeping dread of monarchs awaiting their assassin’s blades, when eyes close and minds float freely into the waiting black, the Plane of Nightmares is where they come ashore. It’s from this twisted realm of infinite and terrible possibility that the terrorborn emerge.</p><p>Strange beings made of a thousand coalesced fears and snatches of stolen memories, the terrorborn wander the Prime Material with an almost childlike curiosity, bearing witness to sights and sounds for the first time unfiltered by the fear of the dreaming. Some terrorborn understand their origins entirely and find themselves strangely delighted by their new form of existence. Others suffer in confusion, lost in the ill-fitting memories of an identity that was never meant to be theirs. In either case, the terrorborn often find themselves drawn to a life of adventure. Some seeking to experience every fresh new thing that corporeal life has to offer, while others are desperately chasing ghosts that cannot provide them with the answers they desire.</p><p></p><h1>Nightmare Ancestry</h1><p>Although the terrorborn are spawned from many fears, each one has a specific nightmare ancestry that makes up the core of their being. This ancestry not only impacts how they look when they reveal their nightmare form but may also impact how they act in the world. A terrorborn whose nightmare ancestry is related to spiders might constantly find themselves toying with the crawling insects and silently relishing the looks of disgust from those around them, while a terrorborn whose nightmare ancestry is taken from the fear of heights might spend their nights running along precarious rooftops.</p><p>When you select this lineage, choose one of the ancestries below to provide inspiration for your character and to determine which of the traits you gain in your lineage’s traits description.</p><p></p><section id=\"secret-6yEmMnpqoSmXen3W\" class=\"secret\"><p><strong>GM NOTES: GUISE AND NIGHTMARE TRAITS</strong></p><p>Each of the nightmare ancestry options includes guise traits and nightmare traits. Guise traits indicate traits that your chosen humanoid form might have while on the Prime Material that hint at their strange origins. Nightmare traits are possible features that are revealed when you use the ability granted by your nightmare ancestry or when you are fully present on the Plane of Nightmares.</p><p>Players should be encouraged to take inspiration from the guise and nightmare traits provided to create their own unique and terrible visage.</p></section><p></p><h3>Heights</h3><p>You are crumbling cliff ledges and towering peaks. Free falls from unforgiving distances and careless slips from window sills. You are made from the dreams of those who fear heights more than anything else that the world has to offer, and as such, you cannot help but feel drawn to those same high places that are responsible for your emergence.</p><p><strong>Guise Traits:</strong> Tall, lanky, sharp features, high hairline.</p><p><strong>Nightmare Traits:</strong> Looming, extra joints, wind-blown garments, empty eye sockets.</p><p></p><h3>Pestilence</h3><p>You are sweating brow and retching stomach. Wounds turned septic, and eyes clouded by unchecked fever. You were born from the fear of disease and sickness witnessed by too many for too long. You are unphased by the presence of your origin and, instead, find yourself endlessly curious about how mortal bodies degenerate and decay.</p><p><strong>Guise Traits:</strong> Pallid, underweight, dark eye circles, wispy hair.</p><p><strong>Nightmare Traits:</strong> Gaunt, yellow eyes, plague masks, clouds of flies.</p><p></p><h3>Spiders</h3><p>You are clinging web and weeping fangs. Chittering mandibles and the predator’s gaze of far too many unblinking eyes. Your birth is tied to the terror inspired by arachnids, great and small. You find that you feel as at home among them as in any dining hall or tavern and never mind inviting one or two of your kin to any place you visit.</p><p><strong>Guise Traits:</strong> Long-limbed, large eyes, pronounced cuspids, coarse hair.</p><p><strong>Nightmare Traits:</strong> Many eyes, mandibles, spider legs, swarms of spiders.</p><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/thedark.png\" width=\"231\" height=\"326\" /><p></p><h3>The Dark</h3><p>You are endless void and crushing black. The haunting possibility of the waiting unseen and of nothing at all. You find your origins in the oldest of fears, of the darkness that hides unspeakable horrors or highlights unbearable emptiness. You wrap the blackest nights around yourself like a treasured cloak and find solace in places beyond the light’s reach.</p><p><strong>Guise Traits:</strong> Dark hair, grey pallor, black eyes, long shadow.</p><p><strong>Nightmare Traits:</strong> Featureless void, black tendrils, endless cloak, shifting size.</p><p></p><section id=\"secret-smRBSRuV4Jnp6P0o\" class=\"secret\"><p><strong>GM NOTES: NEW CREATURE TYPE - NIGHTMARE</strong></p><p>The terrorborn (and the not deer featured later in this supplement) is an example of a new creature type present in the Underground Oracle campaign setting. Nightmares are terrifying beings brought to life by the fears of mortal dreaming and are most often defined by their ability to skew perception and steal hope and inspiration.</p><p>GMs who do not wish to introduce this new creature type into their games can consider relevant creatures aberrations.</p></section><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/terrorborn_edit.png\" width=\"271\" height=\"432\" /><p></p><h3>Terrorborn Traits</h3><p>Your lineage provides you with the following traits.</p><p><strong>Ability Score Increase. </strong>Increase one of your ability scores by 2 and a different score by 1, or increase three different scores by 1.</p><p><strong>Creature Type.</strong> You are a nightmare. You are also considered a humanoid for any prerequisite or effect that requires you to be a humanoid.</p><p><strong>Size.</strong> You are Medium or Small. You choose the size when you choose this lineage.</p><p><strong>Darkvision.</strong> You can see in dim light within 90 feet of you as if it were bright light and in darkness as if it were dim light. You discern colors in that darkness only as shades of gray.</p><p><strong>Speed.</strong> Your walking speed is 30 feet.</p><p><strong>Blood of Fear.</strong> You are made of fear, and yet you do not feel it. You are immune to being frightened.</p><p><strong>Material Guise.</strong> Choose a lineage that doesn’t have a fly speed or swimming speed. You look as though you are a natural member of the chosen lineage. You do not gain any traits provided by the selected lineage.</p><p><strong>Nightmare Ancestry.</strong> As you adventure and your spark grows, your connection to your nightmare ancestry manifests in more powerful ways. At 3rd level, you gain one of the following traits based on the ancestry you chose above. If your selected trait requires a creature to make a saving throw, the DC equals 8 + your Proficiency bonus + your Charisma modifier. Once you’ve used this trait, you can’t use it again until you finish a long rest. When you reach 10th level, you may use this trait twice before needing a long rest.</p><p><strong>Vertigo (Heights Ancestry).</strong> As an action, you trap your foe on the towering peaks that jut from their subconscious. Choose a target creature within 30 feet of you that can see you. The target creature must succeed on an Intelligence saving throw or its speed is reduced to 0, and it is frightened for a number of rounds equal to your proficiency bonus. The target creature may repeat its saving throw at the start of each of its turns or immediately after taking damage. Once a creature has succeeded on its saving throw, it is no longer frightened, and its speed returns to normal.</p><p><strong>Plague Touch (Pestilence Ancestry).</strong> As a bonus action, you brush your fingers across a creature within 5 feet of you that can see you and pull the sickness they fear to the surface. The target creature must succeed on an Intelligence saving throw or be frightened for a number of rounds equal to your proficiency bonus. While frightened in this way, its hit point maximum is reduced by an amount equal to twice your proficiency bonus. The target creature may repeat its saving throw at the start of each of its turns or immediately after taking damage. Once a creature has succeeded on its saving throw, it is no longer frightened, and its hit point maximum returns to normal.</p><p><strong>Swarm (Spiders Ancestry).</strong> As an action, you summon a swarm of crawling horrors from the mind of your victim. Choose a target creature within 30 feet of you that can see you. The target creature must succeed on an Intelligence saving throw or be frightened for a number of rounds equal to your proficiency bonus. While frightened in this way, when the target creature starts its turn, it takes psychic damage equal to twice your proficiency bonus. The target creature may repeat its saving throw at the start of each of its turns or immediately after taking damage from any source other than your illusionary swarm. Once a creature has succeeded on its saving throw, it is no longer frightened, and your illusionary swarm disappears.</p><p><strong>Envelop (The Dark Ancestry).</strong> As an action, you draw the darkness from the nightmares of your adversaries and close it tightly around them. Choose a number of creatures within 30 feet of you equal to your proficiency bonus that can see you. The target creatures must succeed on an Intelligence saving throw or they are blinded and frightened for a number of rounds equal to your proficiency bonus. Affected creatures are still considered frightened by you despite the fact that they cannot see you. The target creatures may repeat their saving throws at the start of each of their turns or immediately after taking damage. Once a creature has succeeded on its saving throw, it is no longer frightened or blinded.</p><p><strong>Languages.</strong> You can speak, read, and write Common, and one other language you and your GM agree is appropriate.</p><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":200000,"name":"Bardic College: College of the Curse Caller","type":"text","_id":"Sa5cXdOLXIXlSIfk","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p></p><blockquote><p>“In our darkest hours, the universe gifts us each a glorious melody. Let me sing yours for you.”</p><p>— Arius VanKellan, College of the Curse Caller</p></blockquote><p></p><p>Life is a symphony composed of both high notes and low. Of triumphs and defeats. Of fortunes and tragedies. Most bards focus on what will inspire and motivate their comrades, touching the Sacred Note to create music that highlights heroes and their grandest victories. But, there are some bards who are unable to see any silver linings when they orchestrate their music, and when they touch the Sacred Note their haunting melodies can only curse those who hear them. Bards from the College of the Curse Caller spend their days composing songs whose somber beauty belies their terrible effects. These forlorn casters use their grim talents to stifle the luck and steal the inspiration of their enemies, making them easier for their allies to incapacitate. Although many Curse Callers bemoan their nature and circumstance, wishing they could share the disposition and abilities of their peers, there are those who take great pleasure in using their jinxed abilities on any who cross them.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Caller’s Dirge</strong></h2><p><em>@UUID[Item.mpdxX5KUs0aD0Zud]{Caller's Dirge}</em></p><p><em>3rd-level College of the Curse Caller feature</em></p><p>When you join the College of the Curse Caller, you learn to twist your curses onto those who hear your doleful melodies. As a bonus action, you may expend a use of your Bardic Inspiration to sing one of the following dirges.</p><p></p><blockquote><h4><em>@UUID[Item.pajeiSGYi87r3Mwx]{The Adventurer's Requiem}</em></h4><p>Choose a creature that can hear you within 60 feet to make a Charisma saving throw. On a failure, for the next 10 minutes, the target creature has disadvantage on ability checks made with an ability of your choice.</p></blockquote><p></p><blockquote><h4>@UUID[Item.IZ53qW36g7BM5hnq]{The Healer's Elegy}</h4><p>Choose a creature that can hear you within 30 feet to make a Charisma saving throw. On a failure, for the next minute or until they regain hit points, any hit points that they would regain are reduced by an amount equal to the result rolled on your Bardic Inspiration die.</p></blockquote><p></p><blockquote><h4>@UUID[Item.BwSD4JluL5j7UrEe]{The Mage's Lament}</h4><p>Choose a creature that can hear you within 60 feet to make a Charisma saving throw. On a failure, until the start of your next turn, creatures affected by the next spell cast by the target creature have advantage on their saving throws. Additionally, if the spell does any damage, roll your Bardic Inspiration die and subtract the amount from the total damage.</p></blockquote><p></p><blockquote><h4>@UUID[Item.2UISGaOeCLgJHvQK]{The Soldier's Monody}</h4><p>Choose a creature that can hear you within 60 feet to make a Charisma saving throw. On a failure, until the start of your next turn, the target creature has disadvantage on attack rolls. Additionally, if their attack does any damage, roll your Bardic Inspiration die and subtract the amount from the total damage.</p></blockquote><p></p><blockquote><h4>@UUID[Item.8YcjBAZmKohEHbzC]{The Stalwart's Hymn}</h4><p>Choose a creature that can hear you within 60 feet to make a Charisma saving throw. On a failure, until the start of your next turn, attacks made against the target creature are made with advantage. Additionally, the first time the creature is dealt damage from a weapon attack, roll your Bardic Inspiration die and add the amount to the total damage.</p></blockquote><p></p><h3><strong>Sublime Calamity</strong></h3><p>@UUID[Item.Y9xwbqOoorN3jjtu]{Sublime Calamity}</p><p><em>3rd-level College of the Curse Caller feature</em></p><p>Your natural aura bedevils those who come close to you. As long as you have any uses of your Bardic Inspiration remaining, creatures within 5 feet of you have disadvantage on the first attack of their turn.</p><p></p><h3><strong>Dismal Harmony</strong></h3><p>@UUID[Item.70Urs7KqfX7f2frR]{Dismal Harmony}</p><p><em>6th-level College of the Curse Caller feature</em></p><p>You’ve learned to take full advantage of the quirks of your jinxed circumstance. You cannot be cursed. If you would be cursed as the result of a spell or ability, you instead regain 1 use of your Bardic Inspiration. Additionally, if you attune to an item that is cursed, you do not suffer from any of its negative effects and may use it without penalty.</p><p></p><h3><strong>Hexed Cantata</strong></h3><p>@UUID[Item.0fvxhfTPLgcifgIO]{Hexed Cantata}</p><p><em>14th-level College of the Curse Caller feature</em></p><p>Your cursed refrains carry on from ear to ear. When you affect a creature with a dirge from your Caller’s Dirge feature, you may expend an additional Bardic Inspiration die to extend the effect to all creatures within 10 feet of the target creature. For each die that you expend beyond the first, you may increase the area of effect by an additional 5 feet.</p><p></p><h2><strong>New Bard Spells</strong></h2><p><em>The following are new bard-specific spells originally derived from the College of the Curse Caller.</em></p><p></p><h3><strong>Failure’s Edge</strong></h3><p>@UUID[Item.O22THPe0JkLyrPXl]{Failure's Edge}</p><p><em>1st-level enchantment</em></p><p><strong>Casting Time:</strong> 1 reaction, which you take in response to a creature within 90 feet of you missing with an attack</p><p><strong>Range:</strong> 90 feet</p><p><strong>Components:</strong> V</p><p><strong>Duration:</strong> Instantaneous</p><p>You hit a sharp note that cuts through the mind of the attacking creature, wounding them with the knowledge of their own failures and weaknesses. The creature must make a Charisma saving throw. It takes 2d8 + 2 psychic damage on a failed save, or half as much damage on a successful one.</p><p>At Higher Levels. When you cast this spell using a spell slot of 2nd level or higher, the damage increases by 1d8 +1 for each slot level above 1st.</p><p></p><h3><strong>Black Dog’s Omen</strong></h3><p>@UUID[Item.JsGqwKgpyiJkSBzA]{Black Dog's Omen}</p><p><em>3rd-level enchantment</em></p><p><strong>Casting Time:</strong> 1 action</p><p><strong>Range:</strong> 60 feet</p><p><strong>Components:</strong> V</p><p><strong>Duration:</strong> Concentration, up to 1 minute</p><p>You sing a song of grim foreboding, clouding the minds of those who hear it. Designate a 20-foot radius area centered on a point within range. During the duration of the spell, creatures that enter the area must make a Charisma saving throw. On a failure, they have disadvantage on attack rolls and saving throws made while in the area. Additionally, each time they fail an attack roll or saving throw while in the area, they take 2d6 psychic damage.</p><p>At Higher Levels. When you cast this spell using a spell slot of 4th level or higher, the damage increases by 1d6 for each slot level above 1st.</p><p></p><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"sort":300000,"name":"Cleric Domain: Broken Bone Domain","type":"text","_id":"2dvBgWy93Y5YKkU8","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p></p><blockquote><p>“Ecrassus is a generous god and a giving master. He allows us all that we can tear from the grasp of others and provides us with eternally smiling servants.”</p><p>— Lysba Valkin, cleric of Ecrassus</p></blockquote><p></p><p>Break the weak, in body and spirit, and take what is theirs, in both this life and the next. These are the tenets clerics of the Broken Bone domain follow, the doctrine of Ecrassus, God of the Skeletal Throng.</p><p>Clerics of the Broken Bone domain are mad cultists, driven by visions from their fallen god of his return and rise to glory. These clerics strive to embody Ecrassus’s ways of bloodshed and domination, spreading fear and violence wherever their sects take hold. Through dark rituals and brutal slavery, they work their captives to death, only to raise them again as their eternal skeletal soldiers.</p><p>@UUID[Item.T7m1yCZN7CzXbiMz]{Broken Bone Domain} @UUID[Item.BBxHl2Mtq3hHMtrL]{Bonus Proficiency (Broken Bone Domain)}</p><h2><strong>Broken Bone Domain Spells</strong></h2><p><em>1st-level Broken Bone Domain feature</em></p><p>You gain domain spells at the cleric levels listed in the Broken Bone Domain Spells table. See the Divine Domain class feature for how domain spells work.</p><p></p><table border=\"1\" style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;width:540px;border-collapse:collapse;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);border-top:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-light-tertiary);margin:0.5em 0px;color:rgb(25, 24, 19);font-family:Signika, sans-serif;font-size:13px;font-style:normal;font-variant-ligatures:normal;font-variant-caps:normal;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:normal;orphans:2;text-align:start;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;widows:2;word-spacing:0px;-webkit-text-stroke-width:0px;text-decoration-thickness:initial;text-decoration-style:initial;text-decoration-color:initial\"><thead style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);color:var(--color-text-light-highlight);text-shadow:1px 1px var(--color-shadow-dark);border-bottom:1px solid var(--color-border-dark)\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Cleric Level</span></td><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">Spells</span></td></tr></thead><tbody style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><tr style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text\"><td style=\"box-sizing:border-box;user-select:text;padding:0.25em 0px 0.25em 2px\"><span style=\"font-family:Signika, sans-serif\">1st</span></td><td 