{"name":"2. HAUNTED WORLD OPTIONS","pages":[{"sort":100000,"name":"Pallowen: Festival of the Frightful Harvest","type":"text","_id":"qitGhP1vRMfLJEAJ","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"image":{},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<p></p><blockquote><p>“Gather, all, for night falls and brings the deepest darkness with it! This is a time that inspires both fear and trepidation, but these tales will protect us from Old Scarwood and his ilk. So long as the terror rings true.”</p><p>- Traditional start to the Warding of Pallowen</p></blockquote><p></p><p>Pallowen, known in some areas of the continent as the Frightful Harvest, is a yearly festival celebrated in honor of the last day of autumn. It acknowledges the blessings gained throughout the year and the role that both good and evil play in people's lives. It is a time to give thanks, but more importantly, it is a day of warding. Warding against not only the darkness of the season to come but also the nefarious creatures and evil spirits empowered during this transitional season.</p><p></p><h2><strong>A Druid’s Sacrifice</strong></h2><p>There are two central figures of the Pallowen festival—Pallowen, the brave halfling druid the holiday is named for, and Old Scarwood, a dark and twisted tree creature full of rot and malice. As the legend goes, a thousand years ago, the specter of a blighted druid tormented the people of the countryside, poisoning their crops and corrupting their forests. After many people valiantly tried and failed to stop the wicked spirit, a humble halfling druid answered the call of the woodlands that depended on her.</p><p>Pallowen battled the foul spirit, but the specter was powerful, more powerful than Pallowen by far. But the druid knew that if she didn’t stop this evil, it would continue to spoil and corrupt the lands she loved. So Pallowen cried out to her god of nature and channeled every bit of earthen energy she could muster from the ground beneath them and into the specter, destroying herself in the process. Her desperate gambit worked, but only partially. The specter could not be destroyed but was instead sealed within a great tree. Its essence merged completely with its wooden prison and has been trapped since that day.</p><p>However, according to the legend, there is one night a year when the spirit, now known as Old Scarwood, is free to roam the world again. The transition between the seasons when all evil is at its most powerful. The day that is now known as Pallowen.</p><p></p><h2><strong>A Festival in Parts</strong></h2><p>A holiday filled with food, costumes, dancing, and stories, Pallowen begins at first light and ends at first light the following day. The traditional celebration is separated into several distinct parts, each representing Pallowen’s battle with Scarwood, though it’s not uncommon for urban areas to focus more on the masquerade and treat-giving aspects of the holiday rather than its more conventional aspects.</p><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Festival_in_parts.png\" /><h1><strong>The Grace</strong></h1><p>The Grace of Pallowen begins at first light and is a time to recognize the bounties of life and the harvest. The community fasts while gathering to decorate and prepare the feast and treats for the day of celebration. Carved pumpkins and straw bales are placed around the community center, and streamers and banners are hung from every home and storefront as decadent cakes, candies, and pastries are made in overt abundance to accommodate the coming festivities.</p><p>When the sun is at its highest, the community breaks its fast and begins the Great Meal—a time for family, friends, and welcomed visitors to come together and show their gratitude for the good in their lives. It’s customary that each person at the table takes a turn to speak their thanks aloud and acknowledge the fruitful gains they’ve made over the season, generally while receiving jovial ribbing and teasing from the others around the table.</p><p></p><h1><strong>The Warding</strong></h1><p>The Warding of Pallowen starts as the feasting ends and the sun begins to hang low in the sky. It’s the time of the holiday to focus on fear and how to face it. It’s a commonly held belief that Pallowen marks the transition between autumn and winter, and that this transitionary period on the Prime Material plane is a time when evil creatures and spirits, led by Old Scarwood himself, are at their most active and powerful. To ward off the creatures of the night and stop them from bringing famineand disease to the community, the people gather together and tell scary stories or legends of great evil. These tales are always told in the first person, as though the speakers themselves were the ones causing the terrors from their stories. The tales are told in this manner to trick Old Scarwood and any other wandering evils into believing that the village has already been claimed by nefarious beings bragging about their conquests, and thus any other villains traveling through the night can continue their search for vulnerable villages.</p><p>The second half of The Warding is full of fun and celebration. Everyone puts on colorful costumes and gathers the treats prepared earlier in the day, placing them in a large Pallowen Basket at the center of the village. After the treats are gathered together, all of the children (and lighthearted adults), who have dressed themselves as various monsters, demons, and villains, begin their parade around the perimeter of the village, winding around the streets and houses and marching past the Pallowen Basket to collect treats wrapped in parchment and scrawled with blessings and prayers for the season to come. After the parade has ended, everyone gathers together for dancing and games, celebrating for as long as they can as midnight approaches.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Costumes and Twisted Tales</strong></h2><p>Although the subjects and fears are localized, dressing up as and telling stories of notorious villains and creatures is the central theme that remains unchanged no matter where Pallowen is celebrated on the continent. Known as a Pallowen Mask, these adopted personas are believed to ensure the safety and prosperity of the community throughout the long dark season to come.</p><p>The @UUID[RollTable.HE8mVvaQLF6hQFx1]{Pallowen Masks} table below provides examples of villainous creatures that are often the subjects of costumes and tales.</p><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Pallowen_Masks_Table.png\" /><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Costumes.png\" height=\"313\" /><p></p><h1><strong>The Sealing</strong></h1><p>The Sealing of Pallowen occurs at midnight and is the time meant to honor and recognize the druid Pallowen’s sacrifice and to protect the village and people during the hard season to come. Midnight on Pallowen—being not only the transition of one day to another but of one season into the next—is believed to be the most dangerous time of the year. As the celebrations and festivities come to a close, villagers giddily rush back to their homes, laughing and scrambling to collect the pieces of parchment containing the good omens and tidings that their neighbors festooned their treats in on the way. To end the evening, and provide the final act of protection for the season to come, they burn the pieces of parchment on the doorsteps of their homes, sending the good wishes and blessings into the ether to join the spirit of Pallowen herself.</p><p>After midnight, the evening is said to belong to the unsavory and wicked forces of the world, both corporeal and spiritual. The custom of staying indoors after the sealing is most strictly adhered to in more rural parts of the world, but within more urban areas it can often mark when the evening’s revelry is just hitting its stride. However, even in remote villages, there are always young and adventurous folk who see it as a test of mettle or a rebellious shirking of superstition to sneak outdoors and experience what the night holds for them.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Festival Activities</strong></h2><p>The activities and games to be experienced during Pallowen can change depending on the country and region where it’s being celebrated, but there are a few typical festivities that accompany nearly every version of the festival.</p><p></p><h3>Harvest Hunt</h3><p>The harvest hunt happens in corn mazes, along labyrinthian woodland trails, or through obstacle courses constructed from tall stacks of straw bales. A favorite seasonal game of the exuberant and athletic, participants take on the role of either hunter or prey, racing through the maze to either corner their quarry or escape the hands of their pursuer.</p><p>The harvest hunt takes place over 6 rounds. Participants playing the role of hunter enter the harvest maze 1 round after the prey. Each round, each prey makes a DC 14 Intelligence check to find their way through the maze. If they are touched by a hunter, they are captured and cannot complete the maze. Hunters touch prey by making a melee attack roll against the prey’s unarmored AC. Prey survives the hunt once they have made 6 successful Intelligence checks without being touched by a hunter. The hunters win if no prey makes it completely through the maze.</p><p></p><h3>Masquerade</h3><p>The masquerade is a gorgeous and lively affair whether it takes place around a bonfire or in an elegant ballroom. Partygoers wear their most elaborate costumes—with more metropolitan guests even enchanting their garb with illusions—and dance and celebrate until moments before The Sealing begins, at which point the Lord of the Masquerade is chosen. Chosen by applause and general audience uproar, the new Lord is presented with a small hawthorn crown and hoisted on the shoulders of their new court before being carried back to their home.</p><p>Over the course of the masquerade, participants may make a DC 14 Charisma check to impress their fellow partygoers and gain their support. On a successful check, the participant gains the support of 5 partygoers, or 10 partygoers if the check succeeds by 5 or more. On a failed check, the participant gains no support or loses the support of 5 partygoers if the check fails by 5 or more. At the end of the masquerade, the participant who has gained the support of the most partygoers is crowned the Lord of the Masquerade. In the event of a tie, the winner is determined by a final contested Charisma check.</p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Masquerade.jpg\" width=\"222\" height=\"397\" /><p></p><h3>Pumpkin Toss</h3><p>A staple of rural celebrations, the pumpkin toss is a Pallowen test of strength where participants gather up carved gourds from their position around the community and attempt to throw them onto tall wooden stakes. Generally started long after the cider and ale have been flowing for hours, the toss is often more of a mirthful act of pumpkin destruction than a true test of skill.</p><p>Participants have 3 chances to land a pumpkin on one of 3 wooden stakes, each painted a different color and set 15 feet apart from one another. Landing a pumpkin on the red stake requires a successful DC 13 Strength check and nets the participant 2 points. Landing a pumpkin on the purple stake requires a successful DC 15 Strength check and nets the participant 4 points. Landing a pumpkin on the gold stake requires a successful DC 17 Strength check and nets the participant 7 points. After the participants have each completed 3 tosses, the one with the most points is declared the winner.</p><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/pumpkintoss.png\" /><h3>Stilt Fight</h3><p>A test of balance and coordination, the stilt fight pits two people on colorful, ribbon-wrapped stilts against one another over a pool filled with autumn leaves—or any other festive, cushiony material. Although attempts to dislodge one another from their perch can lead to spirited scuffles, this contest always ends in laughter and good-humored teasing among the contestants.</p><p>Participants roll initiative at the start of each round. The participant with the highest initiative can attempt to knock over their opponent by making a Strength (Athletics) check contested by their opponent’s Dexterity (Acrobatics) check. If a participant is overcome by their opponent, they can save themselves by succeeding on a DC 14 Dexterity check. Each time a participant must save themselves, the DC for their Dexterity check increases by 2. Once a participant has knocked over their opponent, they are declared the winner.</p><p></p><h3>Warding Parade</h3><p>The warding parade is the heart and soul of Pallowen and the activity most looked forward to by children celebrating the holiday. Not only does it provide the perfect opportunity to show off the costumes that the villagers worked on for weeks, but according to tradition, it also wards away any lingering evil spirits that might try to hide in the community. The fact that it culminates in pulling treats from the Pallowen Basket makes it all the sweeter.</p><p>The below<strong> @UUID[RollTable.r50vB2XZ8L7mohdP]{Pallowen Basket Treats}</strong> table provides examples of what might be pulled from the basket at the end of the warding parade and what blessings might be attached to them.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Plot Hooks</strong></h2><p>The following are plot hooks that you can use to stir up some adventure on Pallowen.</p><p>• While traveling through a great swamp, the party realizes that midnight has passed on Pallowen, and the ominous feeling of being followed settles upon them. The rush to make it back to civilization now begins. On the outskirts of a small hamlet, the group is approached by a terrified young child who tells them that her mother is going to be sacrificed by the locals in an attempt to drive off Old Scarwood.</p><p>• During the Warding of Pallowen, the sound of snapping trees and piercing screams suddenly interrupts the festivities as several blighted and rotten treants amble into the town square.</p><p>• While walking down the street, an unseen force suddenly lifts a small food cart and throws it through a tavern window. Screams can be heard from the building as people spill into the street still dressed in their Pallowen costumes.</p><p>• Raina Pamerra, a local lord, has asked that a nearby dungeon be emptied out before midnight on Pallowen. She fears the evil within will devastate the countryside if left unchecked during this dangerous season.</p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/pallowen_card.png\" width=\"198\" height=\"278\" /><h1><strong>Guilds &amp; Orders: The Order of the Sentinals</strong></h1><p></p><blockquote><p>“All for the cause. All for the realm. All against the darkness.”</p><p>- Order of the Sentinels creed</p></blockquote><p></p><p>The Order of the Sentinels is an ancient and secret society dedicated to protecting mortals from the supernaturally evil threats that work to escape the confines of their planes and wreak havoc on the Prime Material Plane. These brave guardians risk their own lives and souls to ensure that nothing sinister crosses the Veil between the planes and that those creatures that make it through are tracked down and destroyed.</p><p></p><h1><strong>The Darken Veil</strong></h1><p>The Darken Veil is the wall between the Prime Material Plane and all planes and pocket planes dedicated to evil, insanity, and decay. It’s an extraordinary magical barrier said to have been built by the gods as an extra measure of protection upon the existing Planar Veil that creates the gulf between creatures of the Prime Material and the various planes around them. Crossing the Veil between planes is incredibly difficult, but piercing the Darken Veil is nearly impossible for the malevolent forces of the cosmology. However, this layer of protection can be breached by mortals attempting to reach through and contact the powerful dark beings on the other side. Those mortals who willingly peer through the Darken Veil do so at the risk of their sanity, lives, and spirits, but the exchange of power they may receive is too great for them to forego. Each time these individuals reach through the Darken Veil, whether just deep enough to scry or to directly call upon an extraplanar servant, they weaken the barrier and run the risk of something more powerful and dire than they could imagine slipping through.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Malefic Ripples</strong></h2><p>One of the primary tenets among the Order of the Sentinels is that every great tragedy, every terrible event created by the forces of evil, can be traced to a single facilitating moment. These moments of contact with the dark planes, or Malefic Ripples as they’re called by the Order, leave impressions on the Darken Veil that can be found by those trained to sense them. Sentinels spend their time investigating and tracking down the sources of these Malefic Ripples, seeking to eliminate any potentially world-altering schemes in their infancy. Budding necromancers touching the Necrotic Plane, gathering occultists tampering with dark artifacts, warlocks turning to the void, or summoners reaching out for fiendish minions, are all targets of the Order of the Sentinels’ justice.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Who Joins</strong></h2><p>The Order of the Sentinels welcomes people from all walks of life into their ranks, although they specifically seek out and recruit those who have been the victims of the supernatural tragedies and traumas they seek to prevent. After months of investigation and observation, a potential recruit will be approached by a standing member of the order and invited to join their fight against the forces of darkness in any way they can. The members of the Order of the Sentinels are bakers, farmers, warriors, midwives, scholars, and politicians, but above all else, they are enemies of what lies beyond the Darken Veil.</p><p><em><strong>You will thrive in the Order of the Sentinels if:</strong></em></p><p>• You do not trust extraplanar forces or those who use them.</p><p>• You would lay down your life to protect the realm.</p><p>• You are willing to provide whatever you can in service of the cause.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Divisions of the Order</strong></h2><p>The Order of the Sentinels is a society of individuals who share a common goal and general mindset. Members are unpaid, although any wealth or treasure taken by the group is divided evenly among the chapter who found it, with the most wealthy members abstaining in favor of those less fortunate. Sentinels always provide for each other in whatever ways they can, whether it be a place to stay for the night, provisions for a mission to come, or using their political connections to facilitate an objective. The Order of the Sentinels has four divisions spread throughout the realm who work together to keep watch on the world around them and maintain the secrecy of their order.</p><p></p><h3>Sentries</h3><p>Although this is the simplest position in the order, it’s also considered the most important. This division is filled with locals who have few skills and hold humble positions within their communities. Sentries make up the largest numbers in the Order and are the primary source of information distribution among the members. They go about their daily lives as normal, and when they spot any signs of Malefic Ripples in the area, they immediately report this to their assigned contact and continue to watch and wait.</p><p></p><h3>Endowers</h3><p>This division is responsible for supplying the members of the Order of the Sentinels with what they need for their quests and missions for the order. They are usually merchants, outfitters, and blacksmiths of varying types who are well supplied with money and resources.</p><p></p><h3>Seekers</h3><p>This is the most dangerous division in the order. These are the warriors and field investigators who seek out the sources of Malefic Ripples that have been reported. Seekers are willing to do whatever must be done to stop those powers that would cause devastation to society, and that can often lead them down dangerous and illegal paths. Seekers must be careful of not only the dark forces they’re hunting, but of the local law enforcement and officials of the areas they’re in.</p><p></p><h3>Torchbearers</h3><p>Torchbearers are the leaders of the order and generally hold positions of power in their communities. Elders, politicians, and sages are all typically found in this division, and it’s their responsibility to organize and coordinate their local chapter of the Order of the Sentinels. These are the people responsible for removing bureaucratic roadblocks hindering the Order’s members, assigning missions, and clearing up any legal troubles that the Seekers may cause.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Goals</strong></h2><p>The goals of the Order of the Sentinels have remained unchanged since its founding: seek out those who would pierce the Darken Veil and destroy them before they can destroy the innocent mortal lives around them, hunt down any evil creatures who have broken through, and never let the life of one individual outweigh the lives of all.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Guild Features</strong></h2><p>The following options are available to PCs who join the Order of the Sentinels.</p><p></p><h3>Order of the Sentinels (Advanced Background)</h3><p>After surviving a terrible supernatural calamity, you were sought out by a member of the @UUID[Item.EfCqy6gnMufT06JP]{Order of the Sentinels}and recruited. You have completed your esoteric training with the Order and can now spot evidence of intrusion on the Darken Veil.</p><p></p><h3>Feature: Trace the Ripples</h3><p>You can sense and @UUID[Item.4ONcEfmMAu7tZhlO]{locate Malefic Ripples} . You may use Intelligence (Arcana) checks to track and determine the approximate time and location that something attempted to cross or communicate with any evil-aligned plane for up to 1 day after the contact or crossing was attempted.</p><p></p><h3>The Sentinel’s Light</h3><p>Wondrous Item, Major, Uncommon</p><p>This gorgeously crafted lantern is owned by all members of the Order of the Sentinels and kept carefully hidden away unless needed. To the uninitiated, The @UUID[Item.xRZodD4IEItqbZJl]{The Sentinel's Light} looks like a well-made and ornate adventurer’s lantern, but this mystical item is the most important tool in the Order’s arsenal.</p><p>The Sentinel’s Light has 3 charges, and regains all expended charges daily at sunrise. You may spend 1 charge to cast one of the spells below:</p><p>• <em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.BP3GCwa66IAw1yTG]{Daylight}</em></p><p>• <em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.Mzh95utKDPIrjiH8]{Detect Evil and Good}</em></p><p>• <em>@UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.spells.xmDBqZhRVrtLP8h2]{Protection from Evil and Good}</em></p><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Sentinels_Light.png\" width=\"184\" height=\"298\" /><p></p><h1><strong>Cults and Syndicates: The Broken Bone</strong></h1><p></p><blockquote><p>“He is the Ivory Chain! He is the Grinning Master! He is the Deathless Destruction! And we shall make him great again.”</p><p>— Lysba Valkin, cleric of Ecrassus</p></blockquote><p></p><p>Dominance, of not only a body but of a spirit. Control, of not only a life but of the death that comes after. That is what Ecrassus requires from his followers. That is what drives the cult of the Broken Bone.</p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Cults_Syndicates.jpg\" /><p></p><h2><strong>Break the Bones</strong></h2><p>Members of the Broken Bone live their lives in service of Ecrassus, God of the Skeletal Throng. Before he fell from power, Ecrassus ruled over a vast roaming army of skeletal undead that endlessly traversed the Necrotic Plane. A brutal and merciless god-king, Ecrassus commanded his followers to kill, conquer, and subjugate in the worst ways possible, and the worshippers of this fallen deity work to continue his legacy of violence and tyranny from their scattered factions around the continent.</p><p>The Broken Bone exists in small, generally uncoordinated pockets on the fringes of society, among evil tribes of barbarians, or in countries where the opportunity to practice necromancy or slavery without repercussion is available. Although anyone may be mad enough to be taken in by this abysmal sect, the most common followers are those who enjoy the power and dominance championed by this cult or those who have been victims of the same for long enough to become broken and evil themselves. The most common leaders of these cells are clerics, inspired by the nearly forgotten doctrine of Ecrassus and gifted visions from beyond the veil, or necromancers who see themselves in command of their own ivory horde one day. Despite their lack of formal organization, no matter where this cult begins to grow or who is leading them, their methods are fairly predictable, falling in line with the tenets of their malevolent god. And Ecrassus’s demands are as simple as they are immutable; to break the weak and claim all they have to offer. Or, as his followers often chant,</p><p><em><strong>“Break the bones, reap the marrow.”</strong></em></p><p></p><h2><strong>Reap the Marrow</strong></h2><p>Once they have their foothold in an area, the cult will begin scouting out areas to raid. Small villages and farms are particularly vulnerable at this stage, as they typically have the smallest means of resistance and offer the quickest way for the Broken Bone to swell their ranks. After successfully overtaking a village, they will enslave any survivors and begin their darkest works. The cult of the Broken Bone believes that in order to create a true skeletal throng, one that will return their master to his former glory, they cannot simply kill and then raise the remains of their victims. Instead, they combine their necromantic rites with forced labor, ritualistically working their new slaves to death, breaking both their bodies and spirits before adding their skeletons to their burgeoning army.</p><p>The cult will repeat this grisly cycle for as long as they can, attacking larger and larger settlements and growing their numbers until they draw the ire of a contingent strong enough to put an end to their reign of terror, or Ecrassus provides their leader with some new malignant directive.</p><p></p><section id=\"secret-zFKbkwVANK9Elox6\" class=\"secret\"><p><em><strong>GM NOTE:</strong></em></p><p><strong>For altercations with members of the cult of the Broken Bone, utilizing the @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.monsters.CHEUjiYrVM9X0vIT]{Acolyte}, @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.monsters.B7lBOr1AahNZs4a6]{Archmage}, @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.monsters.kz1t6xeXVwODpYb2]{Berserker}, @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.monsters.tYfQIxCJT0WaaKmc]{Cult Fanatic}, @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.monsters.mQnsXanewsPiV7QE]{Mage}, @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.monsters.PVD5wRdyO7iCJPs1]{Priest}, or @UUID[Compendium.dnd5e.monsters.nREPw9g94Bsb9sIl]{Tribal Warrior} stat blocks would all be appropriate, depending on the flavor and difficulty of the encounter you're running. Feel free to alter the spells, weapons, and abilities to match the unique flavor of the cult</strong></p></section><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Reap_marrow.png\" width=\"308\" height=\"301\" /><p></p><h3><strong>Crown of Bone</strong></h3><p><em><strong>Wondrous Item, Artifact (Requires Attunement by a creature of evil alignment)</strong></em></p><p>The @UUID[Item.yeStLimOADMNr156]{Crown of Bone} is the only known holy relic of Ecrassus. An elaborate headdress made of melded bones, this grim artifact is coveted by his followers and provides them with all of the necrotic abilities they need to spread his sinister dogma.</p><p><strong>Random Properties.</strong> The Crown of Bone has the following random properties:</p><p>• 2 @UUID[RollTable.XSMUSA2l1oUbiZ6n]{major beneficial properties}</p><p>• 1 @UUID[RollTable.zY9TGvasG2D15znC]{major detrimental properties}</p><p><strong>Master of Skeletons.</strong> While you are attuned to the Crown of Bone, you can use an action to attempt to dominate any skeletal creatures that are not currently under your control. Select a number of skeletal undead equal to your Wisdom modifier (minimum one) that you can see within 60 feet.</p><p>The targeted undead must make a Wisdom saving throw against your spell save DC. On a failed save, the creatures must obey your commands for the next 24 hours.</p><p><strong>Mighty Throng.</strong> While you are attuned to the Crown of Bone, when you cast the animate dead spell, you may choose bones from any Small, Medium, or Large creature as the target of your spell. Additionally, when you cast animate dead, you may create twice as many skeletons as you normally could with that spell slot.</p><p><strong>Persistent Subjugation.</strong> When you gain control of a skeletal undead through any means, you may double the duration of your control.</p><p><strong>Destroying the Crown.</strong> If the creature attuned to the Crown of Bone has its hit points reduced to zero by radiant damage from a creature with good in its alignment, the Crown of Bone is sent back to the Necrotic Plane, and all undead under their control are immediately destroyed. The Crown of Bone can only be truly destroyed by the willing sacrifice of a Celestial or through divine intervention.</p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/crown%20of%20bone.png\" width=\"220\" height=\"441\" /><p></p><h3><strong>Plot Hooks</strong></h3><p>The following are plot hooks you can use to introduce your players to the cult of the Broken Bone.</p><p>• The eldest daughter of Malcus Valkin has been missing for three months. His search parties have all come up empty-handed. With rumors of raiders growing in the area, and his desperation peaking, the wealthy merchant is willing to offer a fortune to any brave souls who can find her.</p><p>• News has come that Delk’s Peak has been completely overrun by savage barbarians. The few survivors who have managed to escape are telling tales of people being led away in chains and skeletal warriors running rampant.</p><p>• The people at the tavern are all abuzz about the madman who wandered into town overnight. He’s currently sitting in the local jail, ranting about the coming of “the ivory chain” and drawing incoherent scribbles in the dirt.</p><p>• A young acolyte of a local church has been having visions of an approaching skeletal army. No one has given their dreams much thought, but now that rumors of undead lurking in nearby ruins have reached the ears of the Bishop, she’s looking for a group to investigate.</p><p>• After a successful skirmish with a group of orcs, searching their bodies reveals a strange symbol made of human bone and a crudely drawn map to an apparent gathering place.</p><p></p><h1><strong>Infested: Parasites For Your Game</strong></h1><p></p><blockquote><p>“There are thousands of ways to die, millions if you’re really creative. I would take any of them over what did that.”</p><p>- Kinsey Stafford, Apprentice Field Medic</p></blockquote><p></p><p>Adventurers seem to have a habit of going to great lengths to put themselves where they don’t belong. Traversing far-off mountains, exploring dense jungles, or crossing shifting deserts means risking many dangers—both seen and unseen. And before any inexperienced party heads off into the great unknown, they’re often given words of warning and wisdom from their more experienced peers. Told in no uncertain terms that there are ravenous beasts, evil hordes, and supernatural monsters waiting to pounce in the wild places where adventurers are driven to explore, a fresh-faced group might feel emboldened by the knowledge that’s passed their way. But although knowing how to spot and avoid a massive danger will surely prolong the life of a traveling hero, sometimes the gravest threats these areas contain come in the smallest packages.</p><p></p><section id=\"secret-hGnQumUdo4m6MONS\" class=\"secret\"><p><em><strong>GM NOTE, Content Warning:</strong></em></p><p>This new game option introduces an element that some players may find too disturbing to enjoy. Beyond the painful and often grotesque physical symptoms that accompany parasites, these tiny scourges can also bring about feelings of invasion and violation that characters must overcome.</p><p>Whereas some players may find this to be an enjoyable (if somewhat disgusting) obstacle for their character to face, others might find that exploring these particular themes in any way ruins the fun of their game and potential story arc for their character. As with all new rules and game options, it is highly recommended that potentially including parasites in your game is discussed during your pre-campaign conversations or during your group’s session zero.</p></section><p></p><h2><strong>Parasite Mechanics</strong></h2><p>Beyond adding a layer of revulsion and paranoia, parasites bring a new condition into the game—infested. Unless otherwise stated in a parasite’s description block, any spell or effect that detects disease or poison or ends disease or the poisoned condition will detect parasites or end the infested condition as well.</p><p>The effects of being infested are as follows:</p><p></p><h3>Infested</h3><p>• An infested creature has disadvantage on Constitution saving throws and Wisdom (Perception) checks.</p><p></p><h3>Effects</h3><p>In addition to the infested condition, most parasites cause unique effects that are detailed in their description block. The Effect section of a parasite’s block describes the duration, damage, and any other ramifications that an infestation from that parasite may cause.</p><p></p><h3>Becoming Infested</h3><p>Each parasite’s description block indicates how a creature becomes infested with that particular parasite by specifying whether it is external or internal. External parasites are typically contracted by passing through and coming into physical contact with an affected area or object. Internal parasites are generally contracted by a creature introducing the parasite into its system by drinking or eating contaminated materials or receiving an injury from some infested creatures.</p><p></p><h3>Detecting Parasites</h3><p>Parasites, like diseases and poisons, cannot be detected by nonmagical means, although a discerning character could make an appropriate skill check (Arcana, Nature, Medicine, or Survival) to realize the symptoms in another creature and tie them to the parasite in question. The DC for such checks should be determined by the GM as is appropriate to the circumstance.</p><p></p><h3>Harvesting</h3><p>Particularly adventurous characters may attempt to harvest parasites for later use. Should a character detect or discover a source of parasites, via magical or nonmagical means, they can follow the standard rules for harvesting poison to do so. Should they succeed in their necessary skill checks as determined by the GM, they can harvest one use of the parasite. If they fail, they are infested and subjected to the parasite’s effects as normal.</p><p></p><h3>Treatment</h3><p>Outside of spells or features that remove the infested condition from a creature, the most common way to remove parasites is through the use of an antiparasitic. Any character who has proficiency with an Herbalism Kit may create a single dose of a basic antiparasitic over the course of two hours if they have the necessary materials available.</p><p>It should be noted that anything that ends the infested condition on a creature will also end the effects of the parasite affecting them.</p><p></p><h3>Antiparasitic</h3><p>Adventuring Gear</p><p>30 gp</p><p>This @UUID[Item.7mapJQJk84QyOKfL]{potent tincture} provides a creature with advantage on saving throws against infestation for 1 hour or ends the infested condition in a currently affected creature.</p><p></p><p>Some parasites are more exotic, virulent, or magical than others and require one or more special materials in order to make an effective antiparasitic to prevent or treat their infestation. If special materials are necessary, they will be listed in the parasite’s description block.</p><p></p><h2><strong>New Parasites</strong></h2><p>The following are new parasites that you can introduce into your games. GMs should feel free to use the below as templates for creating their own parasites for later use, or to alter the saving throw DCs, durations, or descriptions of those provided to better fit their campaigns.</p><p></p><h3>Dream Eaters (Internal)</h3><p>Dream eaters are leech-like creatures that inhabit the sands of deserts and beaches. They spend most of their lives in hibernation among the dunes, only waking when they sense the presence of a warm-blooded creature in their vicinity. Those unfortunate enough to make camp among the dream eaters stir these parasites from their slumber, causing the worms to slowly climb from the sands and make their way up and into their victim’s ear canal. By the next morning, the throbbing pain in the affected creature’s ears, combined with the constant scritching of the dream eater’s movements, makes sleep and concentration nearly impossible.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Effect:</strong></p><p><strong>Dream eaters cause incessant pain and irritation in the ears of those they afflict. A creature subjected to this parasite must make a DC 13 Constitution saving throw.</strong></p><p><strong>On a successful save, the creature is infested for 2d12 hours.</strong></p><p><strong>On a failed save, the infestation lasts 2d4 days.</strong></p><p><strong>While infested, the creature has disadvantage on Constitution saving throws to maintain concentration and cannot complete a long rest.</strong></p></blockquote><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Parasite1.png\" width=\"231\" height=\"328\" /><h3>Gorgon’s Kiss (Internal)</h3><p>Gorgon’s kiss are minute parasites that dwell on flowers and other vibrant flora, nesting among the pollen that the plants produce. As the wind carries the infested particles through the air, they’re inhaled by unlucky creatures passing through the clouds of spores, at which point the parasites begin their assault on their hosts’ bodies. As gorgon’s kiss moves through the infested creature, feasting on the blood flowing through their bodies, they excrete a substance that crystallizes and hardens, causing increasing amounts of pain and lethargy in their host. Allowed to go unchecked, the victims of gorgon’s kiss are left completely petrified by the crystals throughout their body.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Effect:</strong></p><p><strong>Gorgon’s kiss causes lethargy, pain, and eventual petrification in those they infest. A creature that contracts this parasite must make a DC 12 Constitution saving throw.</strong></p><p><strong>On a failed save, it is infested and immediately gains 1 level of exhaustion. Exhaustion gained by gorgon’s kiss cannot be removed while the afflicted creature is infested.</strong></p><p><strong>Every 4 hours, the infested creature must repeat its saving throw.</strong></p><p><strong>On a failure, it takes 2d6 slashing damage. While infested, if the afflicted creature fails 3 saving throws, they become restrained. After failing 6 total saving throws, the infested creature is petrified until freed by the greater restoration spell or other magic.</strong></p></blockquote><p></p><h3>Hermit Hounds (Internal)</h3><p>Hermit hounds are thin, translucent worms that are found infesting the waters and wildlife of forested areas. Incredibly difficult to see, they’re most commonly encountered by novice adventurers and careless woodsmen who improperly prepare game or drink water tainted with the parasite. After infestation, hermit hounds cause a noticeable change in the personality of their host, making them prone to irritation and paranoia and driving them to become more and more isolated. Once driven into seclusion in the wilderness, the host most typically falls victim to another wild animal or creature that the hermit hounds then pass on to.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Effect:</strong></p><p><strong>Hermit hounds cloud the mind and dull their host’s personality. A creature that drinks water or eats food contaminated with this parasite must make a DC 14 Constitution saving throw.</strong></p><p><strong>On a failed save, the creature is infested for 1d10 days and has disadvantage on all Charisma saving throws and ability checks, avoiding the effects on a success.</strong></p></blockquote><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Parasite2.png\" width=\"232\" height=\"171\" /><p></p><h3>Storm Mites (External)</h3><p>Storm mites are aquatic arthropods roughly the size and shape of a copper piece. In most circumstances, these creatures remain in the shallow tidal pools where they’re born without ever coming into contact with people. However, during periods of monsoons and flooding, minuscule storm mite larvae are swept inland where they burrow under the skin of anyone they touch, creating excruciating clusters of boils and making it almost impossible to wear anything heavier than a loose tunic. After incubating within their host, the mature mites burst out of their host’s flesh, causing even more pain and trauma to their victim’s body.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Effect:</strong></p><p><strong>Storm mites burrow into the skin, causing painful and grotesque boils where they gather. A creature that comes into contact with this parasite must make a DC 15 Constitution saving throw.</strong></p><p><strong>On a failed save, the creature is infested for 1d6 days while the mites incubate. During this period, the pustules caused by the incubating mites make wearing light, medium, or heavy armor impossible. At the end of their incubation period, the mites burst from their host's skin, causing 3d4 piercing damage.</strong></p></blockquote><p></p><h3>Wraith Kin (External)</h3><p>Wraith kin are tiny, transparent jellies that dwell in caves and dank dungeons throughout the realms. They wait on floors, walls, and ceilings in a dormant state until a living creature passes near them, rousing them from their slumber, at which point they attach themselves to their host's flesh. The impact of the wraith kin can be noticed immediately on their host, who finds themself suddenly depleted of their vitality and life force. Given their near-invisible bodies and the draining effects they have on those they infest, they are rumored to be a type of undead, though this is yet to be proven.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Effect:</strong></p><p><strong>Wraith kin attach to their host’s flesh, leeching their energy and spirit. A creature whose flesh comes into contact with wraith kin must make a DC 13 Constitution saving throw.</strong></p><p><strong>On a failed save, the creature becomes infested for 2d6 days, or avoiding the effect on a success.</strong></p><p><strong>While infested, the creature’s hit point maximum is reduced by 4d4.</strong></p></blockquote><p></p><h2><strong>Infesting Spells</strong></h2><p>The following are new infesting spells characters can use to pass along the unwelcome pains of parasites or GMs can use to fill in the spellbooks of their insidious NPCs.</p><p></p><blockquote><p>@UUID[Item.EWGZKXbWNAZejaje]{Infesting Grasp}</p><p>1st-level conjuration</p><p>Casting Time: 1 action</p><p>Range: Touch</p><p>Components: V, S</p><p>Duration: Concentration, up to 1 minute</p><p>You reach out and clutch a target creature, summoning the virulent might of nature’s tiniest terrors. Make a melee spell attack against the target. On a hit, the target takes 1d8 piercing damage and is infested. At the start of each of their turns for the duration, the infested creature must make a Constitution saving throw. On a failure, they take an additional 1d8 piercing damage. On a success, the effect ends on that creature, and they are no longer infested.</p><p>At Higher Levels. When you cast this spell using a spell slot of 2nd level or higher, the damage increases by 1d8 for each slot level above 1st.</p><p>Classes: druid, ranger</p></blockquote><p></p><blockquote><p>@UUID[Item.Uf9u64Dq73nmEhZy]{Cloak of Grotesque Multitudes}</p><p>2nd-level conjuration</p><p>Casting Time: 1 action</p><p>Range: Self</p><p>Components: V, S</p><p>Duration: 1 Hour</p><p>You bite back your revulsion and cover your body with a swarm of parasites that disgusts your opponents and confuses their strikes. Each time a creature targets you with a melee attack during the spell's duration, it must make a Wisdom saving throw. On a failure, the target creature’s attack misses you, and they instead take 1d6 piercing damage and become infested. On a success, the creature’s attack continues as normal.</p><p>This spell ends when your saving throw is failed three times or when you dismiss it as an action. While this spell is active, you have disadvantage on all Charisma-based skill checks but Intimidation.</p><p>At Higher Levels. When you cast this spell using a spell slot of 3rd level or higher, the number of saving throw failures that can be experienced before the spell ends increases by 1 for each slot level above 2nd.</p><p>Classes: druid, ranger, warlock</p></blockquote><p></p><h2><strong>Creature Features</strong></h2><p>The following are a few example features GMs can apply to existing creatures to allow them to access and utilize the rules for parasites presented in this supplement.</p><p></p><p><em><strong>Master of Plagues.</strong></em> When the [name of creature] successfully damages a creature with a spell, the damaged creature must make an additional Constitution saving throw. On a failure, the creature has disadvantage on saving throws made to resist being diseased, infested, or poisoned. This effect lasts until the affected creature completes a long rest.</p><p><em><strong>Revolting Body.</strong></em> When a creature within 30 feet of the [name of creature] targets it with an attack, the attacking creature must succeed on a Wisdom saving throw or that creature cannot select the [name of creature] as the target of their attack.</p><p><em><strong>Teeming.</strong></em> A creature that touches the [name of creature] or hits it with a melee attack while within 5 feet of it must succeed on a Constitution saving throw or take 1d6 piercing damage and become infested. A creature that has already been infested by this feature does not take additional damage from subsequent activations of this feature.</p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Creature_Feature_Image.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /><p></p><h1><strong>Heprion's Guide: Legendary Cursed Items</strong></h1><p></p><blockquote><p>“I’ve spent my life cataloging treasures with extraordinary properties. Over the years, I’ve been lucky enough to cross paths with some truly powerful and miraculous items. These are certainly...powerful.”</p><p>— Foulow Heprion, Heprion’s Vault of Wonders.</p></blockquote><p></p><p>The following is a collection of cursed magic items that provide powerful advantages and equally painful drawbacks to players unlucky enough to come across them.</p><section id=\"secret-eEZNZ4kBNmrxhqQr\" class=\"secret\"><h4><strong>GM NOTES: Unique Items</strong></h4><h4>The items presented below introduce a new designation for magic items; unique. Unique is not a descriptor based on power level but rather describes the singular creation and origin of the item itself. An item with the unique descriptor is a truly one-of-a-kind treasure for a player to discover.</h4></section><p></p><blockquote><p>@UUID[Item.D41MCowl1C14Il2k]{Blood Fangs}</p><p><strong>Weapon (Short Sword), Legendary (Requires Attunement)</strong></p><blockquote><p>These curved short swords are wrapped in beautiful red silk; their vicious edges seem to gleam with their own internal light.</p></blockquote><p><em>Forged using the poisonous metal spiritfell and wrapped in ribbons of siphon’s silk, these weapons were commissioned by the fallen angel Hissigiel for use by her demonic assassins. These cruel blades were used to advance her nefarious goals for years and occasionally find their way to the Prime Material.</em></p><p><em>You gain a +3 bonus to attack and damage rolls made with these magic weapons. The swords have 4 charges and regain all expended charges daily at dusk. You must be in possession of both swords in this pair to utilize their magical benefits, though they only require 1 attunement slot.</em></p><p><em><strong>Venomous Strike.</strong> As a reaction to damaging a creature with these swords, you may expend 1 charge to force the damaged creature to make a DC 15 Constitution saving throw. On a failed save, the target's Constitution score is reduced by 1d4. The reduction lasts until the target finishes a short or long rest. On a successful save, the target instead takes an additional 2d6 necrotic damage.</em></p><p><em><strong>Phantom Strike.</strong> As an action, you may expend 1 charge to make a melee attack against a creature up to 150 feet away that you can see as though they were within your normal melee strike range.</em></p><p><em><strong>Cursed.</strong> The moment that you attune to these weapons, cruel spikes spring from their silk wrapping, driving into your skin and draining your life force. Your hit points are immediately reduced by two hit dice. This reduction lasts until the curse is removed and you break attunement to the weapons.</em></p></blockquote><p></p><section id=\"secret-tDJNutB9hF2GFRVv\" class=\"secret\"><p><strong>Abyssal Materials</strong></p><p>Spiritfell and siphon’s silk are both special materials produced on the Abyssal planes. Although they are incredibly rare, they can be found on the Prime Material from time to time.</p><p><strong>Spiritfell.</strong> Poison saves made as a result of taking damage from a weapon forged with this infernal ore are made with disadvantage.</p><p><strong>Siphon’s Silk.</strong> Generally used in blood magic rituals, items made with siphon’s silk provide arcane benefits in exchange for the user’s life force.</p></section><p></p><blockquote><p><em>@UUID[Item.6So3pA6s9pTR1dRK]{Capridohn’s Magic Bag}</em></p><p><strong>Wondrous Item, Rare (Requires Attunement), Unique</strong></p><blockquote><p>This gorgeously crafted coin purse is made from supple golden leather and lightly vibrates when touched.</p></blockquote><p><em>This magic purse was created by the felonious artificer Reginal Capridohn from the hide of a blink dog. He used it throughout his criminal career to evade the authorities and his many enemies before his mysterious disappearance.</em></p><p><em>Capridohn’s Magic Bag has 3 charges and regains all expended charges daily at dawn, or when you fill it with items or coins equal in value to 100 gold pieces. When you hit a creature with a melee attack, you may expend 1 charge to magically teleport up to 60 feet in any direction to an unoccupied space. This movement does not provoke attacks of opportunity. Additionally, you may expend 1 charge to see 30 feet through any wall for 1 minute.</em></p><p><em><strong>Cursed</strong>. As you attune to this purse, you gain a cursed vision of a massive vault filled with shimmering items and gleaming heaps of gold. Any item or coins placed within this bag are immediately teleported to Capridohn’s hidden vault. Each time you gain any amount of wealth, in items or coins, Capridohn’s Magic Bag requires a tithe equal to at least 10 percent of the value gained. You have one hour to place the required tithe into Capridohn’s Magic Bag or it teleports you 120 feet in a random direction. Items or coins gained to satisfy the tithe during this timeframe do not incur this penalty. This effect remains until the curse is removed and you break attunement to the bag.</em></p></blockquote><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Cloak_ThickenedHide.png\" width=\"212\" height=\"281\" /><p></p><blockquote><p>@UUID[Item.GKUbpyfHncGTnN66]{Cloak of Thickened Hide}</p><p><strong>Wondrous Item, Rare (Requires Attunement), Unique</strong></p><blockquote><p>This dark, rustic cloak is made from an unknown material and lays heavy on the wearer’s shoulders.</p></blockquote><p><em>The exact origins of this cloak are unknown, but it was brought to notoriety while in the possession of the famed mercenary general Gerald “The Warthog” Overhill.</em></p><p><em>While wearing this magic garment, you gain a +3 bonus to AC, and slashing damage you take from nonmagical attacks is reduced by 3.</em></p><p><em><strong>Cursed.</strong> As you attune to the Cloak of Thickened Hide, your skin erupts in thick callouses and protruding warts. Your Charisma score is immediately reduced by 3, and you have disadvantage on Charisma checks. This effect remains until the curse is removed and you break attunement to the cloak.</em></p></blockquote><p></p><blockquote><p>@UUID[Item.mZM2l9N3hZCCsNcy]{Gauntlets of Pyrrus}</p><p><strong>Wondrous Item, Rare (Requires Attunement), Unique</strong></p><blockquote><p>These ornate, ivory gauntlets are inscribed with flourishing runes and symbols lost to time.</p></blockquote><p><em>Created from the bones of the titan Pyrrus, these gauntlets have made a few significant appearances throughout the history of the realms.</em></p><p><em>You must be in possession of both gauntlets in this pair in order to utilize their magical benefits, though they only require 1 attunement slot. While attuned to these gauntlets, you gain the following benefits:</em></p><p><em>• You can lift twice your normal capacity.</em></p><p><em>• You have resistance to bludgeoning damage. Additionally, you take half damage from falling or from something falling onto you.</em></p><p><em>• You gain a +2 bonus to damage rolls made with any melee weapon.</em></p><p><em>Cursed. As you attune to the Gauntlets of Pyrrus, your mind is immediately clouded by the titan’s arrogance and overconfidence. You have disadvantage on Intelligence and Wisdom saving throws and Intelligence and Wisdom checks. This effect remains until the curse is removed and you break attunement to the gauntlets.</em></p></blockquote><p></p><img src=\"modules/under-the-harvest-moons/Assets/Art/Torc_FadingMuse.png\" width=\"338\" height=\"205\" /><p></p><blockquote><p>@UUID[Item.VN6X7qwbKbGxe0yg]{Torc of the Fading Muse}</p><p><strong>Wondrous Item, Uncommon (+1), Rare (+2), or Very Rare (+3) (Requires Attunement by a Bard)</strong></p><blockquote><p>This golden torc seems finely crafted yet feels incredibly delicate to the touch.</p></blockquote><p><em>These torcs were created at the behest of Lord Ezri Kaldova for the personal musicians that provided entertainment for her court. It’s said that Lord Kaldova’s bards were as pale as moonlight and as fleeting as spring snow, but that none could match their grace and charm.</em></p><p><em>While wearing this torc, you gain a bonus to the saving throw DCs of your bard-specific spells and all Charisma (Performance) and Charisma (Persuasion) checks. The bonus is determined by the torc’s rarity.</em></p><p><em>Cursed. As you attune to the torc, you feel your life force wane as haunting music fills your ears. Your Constitution score is immediately reduced by an amount determined by the torc’s rarity. Additionally, checks you make to resist disease are reduced by the same amount. This effect remains until the curse is removed and you break attunement to the torc.</em></p></blockquote><p></p><p></p>","markdown":""},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"flags":{},"_stats":{"systemId":"dnd5e","systemVersion":"2.0.3","coreVersion":"10.288","createdTime":1667069407929,"modifiedTime":1667790550655,"lastModifiedBy":"YQ88Zx2ssDk4TvZ2"},"_id":"ux6Jf0fW38BNg9XG","folder":null,"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0,"YQ88Zx2ssDk4TvZ2":3}}
